Set up the test-train split. There are 1070 observations, so an 80/20 split would provide around 800 rows for training and 200 for testing;

test_index <- sample(1:nrow(juice), size = nrow(juice)*0.2) # random 20% to be used for test

juice_test  <- slice(juice, test_index)   # create test set
juice_train <- slice(juice, -test_index)  # create training set

Tidy the Data for Logistic Regression

It looks like there are several connections between various columns;

  • store7, store_id and store look like they could be connected
  • Several price columns look like they are linked
alias(lm(store ~ ., data = juice_train))
## Model :
## store ~ purchase + weekof_purchase + store_id + price_ch + price_mm + 
##     disc_ch + disc_mm + special_ch + special_mm + loyal_ch + 
##     sale_price_mm + sale_price_ch + price_diff + store7 + pct_disc_mm + 
##     pct_disc_ch + list_price_diff
## 
## Complete :
##                 (Intercept) purchaseMM weekof_purchase store_id price_ch
## sale_price_mm    0           0          0               0        0      
## sale_price_ch    0           0          0               0        1      
## price_diff       0           0          0               0       -1      
## list_price_diff  0           0          0               0       -1      
##                 price_mm disc_ch disc_mm special_ch special_mm loyal_ch
## sale_price_mm    1        0      -1       0          0          0      
## sale_price_ch    0       -1       0       0          0          0      
## price_diff       1        1      -1       0          0          0      
## list_price_diff  1        0       0       0          0          0      
##                 store7Yes pct_disc_mm pct_disc_ch
## sale_price_mm    0         0           0         
## sale_price_ch    0         0           0         
## price_diff       0         0           0         
## list_price_diff  0         0           0

The alias function shows the following;

  • sale_price_mm = price_mm - disc_mm
  • sale_price_ch = price_ch - disc_ch
  • price_diff = price_mm - price_ch + disc_ch - disc_mm
  • list_price_diff = price_mm - price_ch

In addition, it looks like store, store7 and store_id are also connected;

juice_train %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = store, y = store_id) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Store v Store ID")

This plot clearly shows that store and store_id are connected;

  • Store 0 = Store ID 7
  • Store 1 = Store ID 1
  • Store 2 = Store ID 2
  • Store 3 = Store ID 3
  • Store 4 = Store ID 4

So in summary, the following columns can safely be removed;

sale_price_mm, sale_price_ch, price_diff, list_price_diff, store_id, store7

Looking at the ggpairs, it seems like the customer brand loyalty score for Citrus Hill is by far the biggest factor in deciding if any customer bought Minute Maid;

juice_train_trim %>%

Applying brand loyalty score loyal_ch as a first predictor, the first attempt at creating a model can be started;

The calculations above suggest that if a customer’s Citrus Hill brand loyalty score increases by one unit, then the log of the odds of purchasing a Minute Maid decreases by around 6 units.

The problem with trying to make predictions at this stage is that there is currently no threshold set to define at what probability a customer would choose Minute Maid over Citrus Hill. Try 0.5;

threshold <- 0.5

juice_1a_with_pred <- juice_1a_with_pred %>%
  mutate(pred_thresh_0.5 = pred >= threshold) %>% 
  relocate(pred_thresh_0.5, .after = "purchase")

head(juice_1a_with_pred, 10)

The performance of the model can be checked with a confusion table;

conf_table <- juice_1a_with_pred %>%
  tabyl(purchase, pred_thresh_0.5)

conf_table

This shows that the model using loyal_ch as a single predictor correctly predicts true negatives 453 times and true positives 231 times.

juice_1a_with_pred %>%
  accuracy(as.factor(purchase), as.factor(pred_thresh_0.5))

Does this improve with a higher threshold? Can’t think why it would in this case where we only have a choice between one of two drinks, but try 0.6;

threshold <- 0.6

juice_1a_with_pred <- juice_1a_with_pred %>%
  mutate(pred_thresh_0.6 = pred >= threshold) %>% 
  relocate(pred_thresh_0.6, .after = "purchase")

head(juice_1a_with_pred, 10)

The performance of the model can be checked with a confusion table;

conf_table <- juice_1a_with_pred %>%
  tabyl(purchase, pred_thresh_0.6)

conf_table
juice_1a_with_pred %>%
  accuracy(as.factor(purchase), as.factor(pred_thresh_0.6))

So a threshold of 0.6 (78%) is actually less accurate than 0.5 (80%).

Reset threshold back to 0.5;

threshold <- 0.5

Check Model Performance

ROC Curve

roc_obj_1pred <- juice_1a_with_pred %>%
  roc(response = purchase, predictor = pred)
## Setting levels: control = FALSE, case = TRUE
## Setting direction: controls < cases
roc_obj_2pred <- juice_2b_with_pred %>%
  roc(response = purchase, predictor = pred)
## Setting levels: control = FALSE, case = TRUE
## Setting direction: controls < cases
roc_obj_3pred <- juice_3a_with_pred %>% 
  roc(response = purchase, predictor = pred)
## Setting levels: control = FALSE, case = TRUE
## Setting direction: controls < cases
roc_curve <- ggroc(data = list(pred1 = roc_obj_1pred,
                               pred2 = roc_obj_2pred,
                               pred3 = roc_obj_3pred),
                   legacy.axes = TRUE) +
  coord_fixed() + 
  labs(title = "ROC Curve of purchase ~ loyal_ch + price_mm",
       x = "1-specificity (TNR)",
       y = "sensitivity (TPR)") +
  theme_light()

roc_curve

The ROC curve suggests that the 3-predictor model is better than the single and two-predictor models (i.e. it is closer to the top left corner).

AUC

auc(roc_obj_1pred)
## Area under the curve: 0.8617
auc(roc_obj_2pred)
## Area under the curve: 0.8655
auc(roc_obj_3pred)
## Area under the curve: 0.8787

The AUC also backs up the first impressions of the three-predictor model being a better fit to the training data.

Gini Coefficient

The Gini coefficient normalises AUC so that a random classifier has value 0, and a perfect classifier has value 1.

Gini = 2 × AUC − 1

with a possible range of values

−1 ≤ Gini ≤ 1

Although, as for AUC, the practical range is

0 ≤ Gini ≤ 1

gini_1pred <-  2 * auc(roc_obj_1pred) - 1
gini_1pred
## [1] 0.7234097
gini_2pred <-  2 * auc(roc_obj_2pred) - 1
gini_2pred
## [1] 0.7309907
gini_3pred <-  2 * auc(roc_obj_3pred) - 1
gini_3pred
## [1] 0.7573643

The Gini coefficient also backs the theory that the three predictor model is a better fit to the training data.

  mutate(pred_thresh_0.5 = pred >= threshold) %>% 
  relocate(pred_thresh_0.5, .after = "purchase")

An overall accuracy of 82% is similar to the training set, which suggests minimal overfitting.

The True Positive Rate is 89%, which seems quite good.

A True Negative Rate of 71% also corresponds well with the training set.

Summary

Overall a three-predictor model has been found to be the best model for predicting whether or not a customer might buy Minute Maid or Citrus Hill, according to the relationship;

\[purchase_{(MM\ or\ CH)} \sim CH\_brand\_loyalty + price\_MM + discount\_MM\]
